    "troubleshooting": [
      {
        "symptom": "Guacamole turns brown quickly",
        "likely_cause": "Oxidation from air exposure",
        "prevention": "Press plastic wrap directly onto the surface of the guacamole when storing, eliminating all air pockets.",
        "fix": "Scrape off and discard the top oxidized layer before serving; the guacamole underneath will be perfectly green."
      },
      {
        "symptom": "Guacamole is too tart or acidic",
        "likely_cause": "Too much lime juice or overly acidic pickled peppercorn brine",
        "prevention": "Rinse pickled peppercorns lightly before using and add lime juice incrementally.",
        "fix": "Fold in half of a freshly mashed avocado to dilute the acidity, or add a tiny pinch of sugar."
      }
    ],
    "chef_notes": [
      "For the best texture, ensure your avocados are perfectly ripe; they should yield to gentle pressure at the stem but not feel entirely mushy.",
      "Using pickled green peppercorns adds both acidity and a mild, herbaceous heat. Rinse them briefly if you want to control the impact of the brine.",
      "Raw tomatillos add a crisp, tart crunch that perfectly cuts through the rich avocado, acting as a textural contrast to the soft peppercorns.",
      "Pounding a small amount of the aromatics with salt creates a flavor base that seasons the dip more evenly than simply stirring the ingredients together."
    ],
    "cultural_context": "Guacamole originated in Central Mexico, where it has traditionally been prepared by pounding ingredients in a volcanic stone molcajete. This Southwestern interpretation bridges culinary traditions by introducing the briny, floral bite of pickled green peppercorns, an ingredient more commonly associated with French or Southeast Asian cuisines. The addition of raw tomatillo reinforces the regional Southwestern profile with a bright, crisp acidity.",
